s, and Bases tells a missing, racialized history of the U.S. migration detention system that was developed and expanded to deter Haitian and Cuban migrants. Jenna M. Loyd and Alison Mountz argue that the U.S. response to Cold War Caribbean migrations established the legal and institutional basis for contemporary migration detention and border-deterrent practices in the United States. This book will make a significant contribution to a fuller understanding of the history and geography of the United States’s migration detention system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlien detention centerszUnited States. 0aDetention of personszUnited States. 0aIllegal aliensxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aIllegal immigrationxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aNoncitizen detention centerszUnited States. 0aNoncitizensxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aNoncitizens. 0aRefugeeszCaribbean AreaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aMountz, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520962965?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962965/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles